The 'bee coche' that prevents collisions
To advance in the development of technologies for accident prevention Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, in particular, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C that is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, BR23C is presented as an extension of the Safety Shield in four areas of Nissan.
This robot intends to strengthen the ability to prevent collisions of brand vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own personal space in an oval shape that looks a lot like the Nissan Safety Shield.
But the most important thing is bee's compound eyes, capable of seeing with an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, which allows you to fly without interruption within your own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they called a laser tracker (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles up to two metres away within 180-degree radius in front of BR23C, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to an approach microprocessor that immediately translates into collision prevention.
"At the moment you detect an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a straight angle or larger to avoid collision.
The greatest difference with any existing system is that the escape maneuver is completely instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and major engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted up or down, or diagonally; it can only be moved in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and slowing down, so that the little robot avoids collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act according to that data.
It does not require to store information or intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can work continuously with only a couple dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we're not talking about memory gigs, not even megas."
This is the first step in developing new technologies for instantaneous collision prevention, a technology that Nissan vaccine will introduce into serial cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles on the way.
