Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
To refound the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the common project of the Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, was the third to vote on a draft for a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished as 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to the official results of 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28 %, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7 % were blank.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it would have to obtain half the plus one suffrage.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the electoral centres and a count of a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory to the "yes", estimated from 63% to 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on Sunday night to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The " Constitution triumphed in a crushing manner " , he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who lead the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometres southwest of Quito.
So Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by her Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will take place in full calm, according to the observer mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text of 444 points consolidating the " new socialism " defended by the President.
The draft Constitution implies increasing the power of the State over the economy, reserving the " development planning " of a country that essentially lives through the extraction of oil by foreign companies and foreign currencies that send their emigrants.
With the exception of Correa, elected in 2006, the draft also grants strengthened powers to the head of State, which may carry out up to two consecutive mandates of four years each and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa had already announced that she would use this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50 per cent of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for the ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as the starting point for American drug operations.
The 19 kidnapped people have been released in Chad
An Egyptian command launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by the Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked good at their arrival at 3:30 p.m. on board a special plane to the military base of Al Maza, adjacent to the international airport of Cairo.
They were immediately transported by helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, to be subjected to medical tests, so they were unable to speak to the press.
"They find themselves healthy" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian tourism minister Zohair Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages fell in possession of 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying a safari in allterrestrials in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and since then they have moved from one safari to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border guard and the director of the travel agency Egyptus, in charge of the organisation of the safari.
An Egyptian security officer indicated that 30 members of the special forces, transported on board two helicopters, had launched the assault at night before dawn.
"An exchange of shots occurred, and killed half the kidnappers, the others have fled," said this responsible who kept the anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces were sent to Sudan, where they had the support of German and Italian commanders.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of Italian special forces.
"It must be acknowledged that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men in the secret services, the special forces," he said without going into detail.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
On the eve of the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an all-terrestrial on board which were the kidnappers, of whom he killed six, including the Chadian chief and arrested two.
He also stated that they were related to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-United Nations Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a statement that was immediately denied by that group.
