The Governments of the Netherlands nationalize a part of the Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with nationalisation the Belgian-Netherlands bank Fortis which is in trouble due to the impact of the mortgage crisis of the US market: the three countries will support in total EUR 11.2 billion to this financial and insurance institution which also has businesses in Hungary.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held higher-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the Head of Economic Competition of the European Commission.
Fortis Bank is the first to suffer from the crisis in the euro area in the context of the international financial crisis that has been taking place in several waves more than a year ago, so decisions made with regard to the Bank can in some sense be regarded as precedents.
According to the decision taken in the early morning of Sunday, the three States will purchase approximately half (49 percent) of the property owned by the Bank in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell part of its business, including most of the activities - mainly insurance - purchased last year of ABN Amró Dutch.
The actions of the Fortis began a strong decrease last week and by the second half of the week there were already important signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree to point out that with their 85,000 employees this Bank is too large to allow it to break down.
The company's actions only on Friday decreased by 12 percent, this being the lowest point in the last 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares has decreased by more than two thirds.
By observing the current prices of the shares, the total value of the group’s capital on the market is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the company’s executives this is not real.
The Bank's leadership imposed the sudden fall of Fortis' actions on the insecurity of the US market in relation to the approval of the US package plan of $700 billion.
On Monday the actions already showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the new CEO of the bank.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a specific offer.
The Belgian government had already said that investors had nothing to worry about, they would not lose their money.
Among the Bank’s customers so far there was no panic, they did not invade bank offices to withdraw their money.
El Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
